items.subtitle: Reviewed in Germany on 23 October 2023
items.title: Hervorragende Qualität und perfekte Passform für das iPhone 15 Pro
items.review_text:
Die TORRO Hülle für das iPhone 15 Pro hat mich von Anfang an überzeugt. Leider bietet Apple keine Echtleder Schutzhüllen an, deshalb habe ich der Hülle von TORRO eine Chance gegeben.
Die Qualität der Teile, aus denen die TORRO Hülle gefertigt ist, ist beeindruckend. Das hochwertige Leder fühlt sich nicht nur angenehm in der Hand an, sondern strahlt auch Langlebigkeit und Stil aus. Im Vergleich zu anderen Hüllen auf dem Markt, die oft minderwertige Materialien verwenden, um Kosten zu sparen, sticht die TORRO Hülle deutlich hervor.
Die Passform der Hülle ist ein weiteres Highlight. Sie schmiegt sich perfekt um das iPhone 15 Pro, wirkt dabei allerdings etwas sperrig. Wer eine möglichst dünne Hülle haben möchte, sollte hier lieber nicht zugreifen. Alle Aussparungen für Kamera, Lautsprecher, Tasten und Anschlüsse sind millimetergenau positioniert, was die Bedienbarkeit des Geräts in keiner Weise beeinträchtigt. Selbst nach längerem Gebrauch bleibt die Hülle fest an Ort und Stelle, ohne sich zu lockern oder unschöne Spuren zu hinterlassen.
Die Verarbeitung der TORRO Hülle ist einfach erstklassig. Die Nähte sind präzise und langlebig, und die Knöpfe sind reaktionsschnell und leicht zu bedienen. Diese Hülle verleiht dem iPhone 15 Pro nicht nur einen Hauch von Eleganz, sondern schützt es auch zuverlässig vor Stößen, Kratzern und Schmutz.
Was mir besonders gefällt, ist das durchdachte Design. Die Hülle verfügt über praktische Kartenschlitze, in denen ich meine Kreditkarten oder Ausweise sicher aufbewahren kann.
Zusammenfassend kann ich die TORRO Hülle kompatibel mit dem iPhone 15 Pro nur wärmstens empfehlen. Die Qualität der Materialien und die Passform sind unübertroffen, und sie bietet einen stilvollen Schutz für mein wertvolles Smartphone. Investieren Sie in die TORRO Hülle, und Sie werden verstehen, warum sie sich von der Konkurrenz abhebt.

items.subtitle: Reviewed in the United States on 2 October 2023
items.title: How Do I Get Rid of the Smell?
items.review_text:
Preface:
As a "for fun" tester of many phones, I always try to find the book cover style leather phone cases.
I didn't read any of the specs before hand, but I saw a case on preview image that didn't look as bad as others and bought it. Luckily not a mistake.
The Use Case:
I have been using it for the past week or so that the phone has become available and though it may not be a large enough time frame to truly put the case through its paces, I can say I am rougher with this phone cases than I have been with my older ones. Constantly running miles with a phone in my pants pocket, resting it in random places, and sliding it rather than picking it up and moving it when I'm trying to get something in its way.
It's a really long-winded review so let me bring up the closing and recommendations and breakdown further down. Just make sure to read the final thoughts at the very bottom if you are skipping the breakdown segments.
Closing / TL:DR:
On the surface level, you get what you expect out of a case of this style.
It is indeed a luxury item, but it feels a necessity and should be a proper baseline for similar products to come.
It's worth the money considering it offers the basic necessities and it protects a product about 20 times its cost well.
Should You Buy It:
Probably not if you're majorly OCD because some pieces do not sit flush and it might drive you crazy if you sit and stare at it.
You probably not buy it if actual leather or leather labeled products are a problem to you.
You should buy it if you can't find anything better for a cheaper price.
The Breakdown - Materials:
-The Leather Cover
There is smooth, and evenly finished leather (ignoring the punched out portions for the logos) which hasn't begin showing any signs of wear with all the friction I think it goes through on my day to day use.
The front flap feels there should have been something stiffer inserted between the seems to actually offer more than scratch protection (that is my rationale before and after adding cards into the pockets).
The front flap could have done with another 1/6th - 1/8th an inch of insert so that it can squarely rest on the plastic case holding the phone itself.
The leather itself could have been thicker to match the levels of the plastic phone case but that's a small detail that doesn't affect the quality.
-The Plastic Case
There is a plastic case glued to the leather which feels the right amount of sturdy for short falls and scratch protection.
The material is nice but it seems it could have been better contoured/molded to create a more flushed feel.
-The Adhesive
The factory glue which binds the leather to the plastic always separates right underneath the camera. It's not unique to this case, but with a little super glue it always goes back on and holds.
The Breakdown - Usability:
Once you get the case on and you get over the worry you've broken a button, you are now able to explore and use the case.
-The Leather Cover
You get three front pockets that will fit cards securely (though I never put cards of great value in my phone case) and isn't offensive to remove the cards.
Front pockets aside you also get a pocket behind the card holders for bigger notes, money, more cards and etc.
(Over time you do work markings from the case onto the phone screen so be careful how full you stack the pockets. It comes with the territory if you have your phone in your pocket and you regularly apply pressure to it as you move around.)
All in all, it makes it easy to pick up and hold and not too much extra weight for the expected extra bulk.
-The Plastic Case
There is attention to detail here as there should be, where the case has a camera well, that elevates the phone off of the surface. It's a small design feature sometimes forgotten but makes the biggest of differences such that if you're resting your phone on smooth surface you will never risk the cameras touching the surface.
The camera well does not obstruct the camera in any way and it's perfect as is.
The phone case seems stiffer on one side than the other where the volume buttons can't be adjusted without properly wanting to and at the same time soft enough where the lock button lies to press quickly to access wallet and hold for Siri.
If you're going for a screenshot, you're likely to miss a few times and just lock your phone and it's to be said when you're changing the volume up or down and your finger is accidentally resting on the lock, you'll also press that by accident sometimes.
(You can work on a better pinch or you can slow down and force yourself onto the right presses)
Plugs and speakers are. unobstructed.
Final thoughts:
I can go on, but for day to day it's really functional.
Honestly though, I want to know how to get rid of this chemical smell that comes from either the adhesive or finishing steps for the case. It's been driving me mad since I got it.

items.subtitle: Reviewed in the United Kingdom on 5 October 2023
items.title: Dissatisfied, comfort issues
items.review_text:
I am dissatisfied with this purchase. Whilst the case seems to be made of decent quality materials, it does not fit iPhone 15 pro well.
My biggest complaint is that the phone sits too deep in the case so the case edges stick out too far which makes corner-swipe gestures a lot more difficult to perform. When the phone is held in one hand such swiping becomes even harder.
My second complaint is that the new iPhone 15 series side button is barely reachable. My fingers are relatively thin, but I can press the button only using my index finger nail (with some effort!)
The third complaint is that the magnetic lock on the side may become an issue because it is quite hard and stick out far enough to cause discomfort, particularly when the phone is held in one hand.
As I said in the beginning of this review, I like the materials and design of the case, but the fit issues are annoying.
Hopefully, this review will be seen and considered by the manufacturer with a view on improving this product.
